You can use the following JavaScript code to check if the highlighted text is more than 100 words, including Chinese:
```javascript
// Get the highlighted text
var highlightedText = window.getSelection().toString();

// Use a regular expression to match Chinese characters
var chineseRegex = /[\u4e00-\u9fa5]/;

// Split the highlighted text into an array of words
var words = highlightedText.split(/\s+/);

// Initialize a variable to count the number of Chinese characters
var chineseCount = 0;

// Iterate through the array of words
for (var i = 0; i < words.length; i++) {
    // Check if the current word contains Chinese characters
    if (chineseRegex.test(words[i])) {
        // Increment the Chinese character count
        chineseCount++;
    }
}

// Check if the total number of words, including Chinese characters, is more than 100
if (words.length + chineseCount > 100) {
    console.log("The highlighted text is more than 100 words, including Chinese.");
} else {
    console.log("The highlighted text is less than or equal to 100 words, including Chinese.");
}
```
This code uses the `window.getSelection().toString()` method to get the highlighted text, and the `split()` method to split the text into an array of words. It then uses a regular expression to match Chinese characters in the words.
It uses a for loop to iterate through the array of words and a if condition to check if the current word contains Chinese characters and increment a variable `chineseCount`
Finally, it checks if the total number of words, including Chinese characters, is more than 100.
Please note that this code will only work if it's executed in the context of a web page and the user has highlighted some text on the page.

You can use the following JavaScript code to check if the highlighted text is more than 100 Chinese or English words:
```javascript
// Get the highlighted text
var highlightedText = window.getSelection().toString();

// Use regular expressions to match Chinese and English characters
var chineseRegex = /[\u4e00-\u9fa5]/;
var englishRegex = /^[A-Za-z0-9]+$/;

// Split the highlighted text into an array of words
var words = highlightedText.split(/\s+/);

// Initialize variables to count the number of Chinese and English words
var chineseCount = 0;
var englishCount = 0;

// Iterate through the array of words
for (var i = 0; i < words.length; i++) {
    // Check if the current word contains Chinese characters
    if (chineseRegex.test(words[i])) {
        // Increment the Chinese word count
        chineseCount++;
    }
    // Check if the current word contains only English characters
    if (englishRegex.test(words[i])) {
        // Increment the English word count
        englishCount++;
    }
}

// Check if the number of Chinese words is more than 100
if (chineseCount > 100) {
    console.log("The highlighted text contains more than 100 Chinese words.");
} 
// Check if the number of English words is more than 100
else if (englishCount > 100) {
    console.log("The highlighted text contains more than 100 English words.");
}
else {
    console.log("The highlighted text contains less than or equal to 100 Chinese or English words.");
}
```
This code uses the `window.getSelection().toString()` method to get the highlighted text, and the `split()` method to split the text into an array of words.
It then uses regular expressions to match Chinese and English characters in the words. It uses a for loop to iterate through the array of words and two if conditions to check if the current word contains Chinese or English characters respectively. If it does, it increments the variable `chineseCount` or `englishCount` respectively.
Finally, it checks if the number of Chinese or English words is more than 100.
Please note that this code will only work if it's executed in the context of a web page and the user has highlighted some text on the page.

